      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>banner ad</strong> is a rectangular graphic advertisement displayed on a webpage, usually across the top, sides, or bottom. Banner ads use static images, animated GIFs, HTML5, or rich media to drive brand awareness and click-throughs, and are bought through display networks and programmatic exchanges.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Format</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Image, GIF, HTML5</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Paid Advertising</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Avg CTR</div>
            <div class="tms-value">0.05% &ndash; 0.10%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Foundational</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The banner ad is the oldest form of paid digital media &mdash; the first one, an AT&amp;T banner on HotWired, ran in October 1994. Thirty years later banner ads are still one of the highest-volume ad formats on the internet, largely because they offer the cheapest reach in digital. The economics only work when you know exactly what job you are hiring them to do.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a banner ad?</h2>
        <p>A banner ad is a graphic advertisement embedded on a webpage. It usually sits in a fixed slot &mdash; leaderboard at the top, skyscraper along the side, medium rectangle in the article, or mobile banner at the bottom. When a user clicks the banner, they are taken to the advertiser's landing page. Impressions, clicks, and (increasingly) attention are counted and reported to the buyer.</p>
        <p>Banner ads come in several forms:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Static image</strong> &mdash; a single JPG or PNG frame</li>
          <li><strong>Animated GIF</strong> &mdash; simple looping animation</li>
          <li><strong>HTML5</strong> &mdash; interactive, animated, video-capable creative in code</li>
          <li><strong>Rich media</strong> &mdash; expanding, interactive, or video-enabled banners</li>
          <li><strong>Native display</strong> &mdash; banners styled to look like editorial content on the host site</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Context</div>
          <p>The IAB standardised the most common banner sizes, and Google Display Network reports that four sizes drive the majority of display ad impressions worldwide: 300x250 (medium rectangle), 728x90 (leaderboard), 160x600 (wide skyscraper), and 320x50 (mobile banner).</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why banner ads matter</h2>
        <p>Banner ads look outdated to many marketers, but they remain the workhorse of the open web for good reason.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Cheap reach at scale.</strong> Display CPMs are usually $1 to $5, an order of magnitude below social or search. That makes them the most affordable way to keep a brand present.</li>
          <li><strong>Retargeting powerhouse.</strong> The most effective banner campaigns re-serve ads to people who already visited your site. Retargeting banners routinely produce 5 to 10x the CTR of prospecting banners.</li>
          <li><strong>Programmatic infrastructure.</strong> Display ad exchanges made real-time bidding the standard model of digital media. Everything from CTV to audio ads inherits that plumbing.</li>
          <li><strong>Creative testing lab.</strong> Cheap impressions make banners a low-risk place to test headlines and creative ideas that later graduate to more expensive channels.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How banner ads work</h2>
        <p>Modern display buys run through programmatic auctions. Every impression is auctioned in real time between hundreds of advertisers, and the winning bid gets the ad slot.</p>

        <h3>The core mechanics</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># The RTB (real-time bidding) lifecycle</span><br>
          User loads a page &rarr; <span class="uf-label">SSP requests bids</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&darr;<br>
          DSPs bid on the impression <span class="uf-comment">(&lt;100ms)</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&darr;<br>
          Highest bid wins &rarr; <span class="uf-status">creative served</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&darr;<br>
          User sees banner &rarr; may click &rarr; lands on advertiser page
        </div>

        <h3>Where banner ads connect to your broader strategy</h3>
        <p>Banner ads rarely produce results in isolation. They shine as a layer inside a full-funnel plan: prospecting on paid social, retargeting on display, closing on search. The layer is what compounds &mdash; not any single format.</p>

        <h3>What good looks like vs what bad looks like</h3>
        <p>The gap between the top and bottom quartile of banner ads is enormous. Winning banners are visually distinctive, load in under 100 KB, feature the brand within the first two seconds, and carry a single call to action. Losing banners look like everything else on the internet.</p>

