        <h2 id="examples">Real banner ad examples</h2>
        <p>Three patterns that make display work in 2026:</p>

        <h3>1. Retargeting the cart abandoner</h3>
        <p>Ecommerce brands routinely retarget users who added a product to cart with a 300x250 banner that shows the exact product plus a small incentive. Conversion rates on retargeted cart carriers can be 3 to 10x higher than prospecting display.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B awareness inside a category publication</h3>
        <p>SaaS vendors buy 728x90 leaderboards on niche industry publications their ICP reads (e.g. finance ops or DevOps outlets). The goal is not the click &mdash; it is the fifth impression that makes the brand feel familiar when the buyer eventually searches.</p>

        <h3>3. Native display for content upgrades</h3>
        <p>Publishers-turned-marketers use native display units that match the host site's article style to promote long-form guides. CTRs frequently 3 to 5x IAB-standard display formats because they look like editorial and disclose only lightly.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 banner ad best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Design for the first 200 milliseconds.</strong> Banners get scanned, not read. Make sure the brand, the offer, and the CTA are legible in the first frame.</li>
          <li><strong>Test creative in volume.</strong> Ship 5 to 10 concepts per campaign; let the platform decide which one wins. Static winners often beat animated challengers.</li>
          <li><strong>Match creative to the placement.</strong> A leaderboard needs a different composition from a mobile banner. Design each size fresh &mdash; do not just resize.</li>
          <li><strong>Retarget aggressively, prospect selectively.</strong> Most display budgets deliver 3 to 5x more ROI on retargeting than prospecting.</li>
          <li><strong>Cap frequency.</strong> The same user seeing the same banner 30 times a week is not five times better than seeing it six times &mdash; it is worse. Cap at 3 to 8 per week per user.</li>
          <li><strong>Exclude the brand-safety-poor placements.</strong> Pre-built inclusion or exclusion lists dramatically improve where your brand shows up.</li>
          <li><strong>Track viewability, not just impressions.</strong> An impression that is never in the viewport does not exist. Buy against MRC-viewable inventory.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap &mdash; banner blindness</div>
          <p>Users have trained themselves to ignore anything that looks like an ad. Standard-format banners on standard placements produce click-through rates below 0.1%. Assume attention is scarce; design accordingly, and pair banners with paid social or search to close.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common banner ad mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Buying prospecting-only display.</strong> Without retargeting, most display budgets underperform paid social and search.</li>
          <li><strong>Cluttered creative.</strong> Too many products, offers, or logos in one banner &mdash; users scan past.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring mobile.</strong> Over 60% of display impressions are mobile; treating mobile banner as an afterthought caps performance.</li>
          <li><strong>No frequency cap.</strong> Burning through impression budget on a small group of users kills ROI.</li>
          <li><strong>Landing pages that do not match the banner.</strong> Every click deserves a page that echoes the ad's headline and offer; anything else leaks conversion.</li>
        </ul>

